default              
defaultThis submission is made by POhWER, an advocacy charity established over fifteen years ago by service users who felt unequal to the task of voicing concerns about decisions made by public bodies on matters that affected their day to day lives.
default&#xa0;
default2
default              
defaultWe provide NHS complaints advocacy services from the outset. We focus particularly on people who are vulnerable, distressed or drawn from the protected equality groups.
default&#xa0;
default3
default              
defaultLast year alone, we handled over 30,000 calls about the NHS complaints process to our information, advice and advocacy centre and provided over 4,000 people with direct advocacy support. We can draw on the experiences of all these clients to provide you with evidence based views on the Parliamentary and Health Service 
defaultOmbudsman
default.
default&#xa0;
default4
default              
defaultOur focus in this submission is on the second tier of the NHS complaints handling process. 
defaultT
defaulthe first tier 
defaultwas designed with substantial complainant involvement and feedback from our clients suggests that it has the potential to deliver the 
defaultkind of approach and the outcomes 
defaultthey seek. However, it 
defaultsuffers from poor implementation and has not kept pace with the recent NHS changes. 
defaultUnfortunately our experience with the second tier, when cases are taken to the Ombudsman, is not so positive. This is particularly worrying in an organisation that is a specialist complaint handler.
default&#xa0;defaultParliamentary and Health Service Ombudsmandefault&#xa0;
default5
default              
defaultSo far this year, since April 2013, 8% of our NHS cases were referred on to the Parliamentary and Health Service Ombudsman (PHSO). In previous years, we have referred around 15% of cases to PHSO.
default The reason for this seems
default to be a growing reluctance to 
defaultuse the Ombudsman service because of the experiences of others.
default&#xa0;
