defaultinterpreted wrongly or not stated clearly. In one case where our client objected to the summary of her complaint, her case was ‘withdrawn’ 
defaultby PHSO 
defaultas she would not consent for her truncated complaint to be sent to the Trust as her complaint.
default This
default appears to run against 
defaultthe
default intention of the
default Health Service Ombudsman Act 
defaultwhich states:
default&#xa0;
defaultProcedure in respect of investigationsdefault.
defaultE+W+S+N.I.default(1)Where a Commissioner proposes to conduct an investigation pursuant to a complaint under 
default[defaultF1defaultsection 3(1)
default]default, he shall afford— 
default(a)to the health service body concerned, and 
default(b)to any other person who is alleged in the complaint to have taken or 
defaultauthorised
default the action complained of, 
defaultan opportunity to comment on 
defaultany allegationsdefault contained in the complaint. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThis surely means that PHSO should not paraphrase
default the meaning of a complaint or reduce it to what they think t
defaulthey can achieve.
default 
defaultAt the very least they need to explain to complainants why they feel no worthwhile outcome can be obtained on the aspects that they propose not to investigate so that complainants have a chance to challenge this.  By the time they have reached the Ombudsman, most complainants are battle weary. They would not be pursuing the case if they did not feel a strong sense of injustice.  The Ombudsman is their last hope –  surely incumbent on her to do her best to investigate or explain fully why she feels there is nothing useful to be achieved.
