default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe feel that PHSO 
defaultwould benefit from
default the following.
default&#xa0;
default17
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultBeing more customer focused. defaultA
defaultt POhWER
default,
default we ensure we contact our clients on a regular basis, to keep them updated and to 
defaultensure they clearly understand what is 
defaulthappening
default. We also ensure that there is complete transparency and share documentation with our clients whenever possible.
default PHSO would be better if it improved its communication and openness with complainants.
default&#xa0;default18
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultHaving an defaultexternal review of its processesdefault. defaultC
defaulturrently 
defaultPHSO’s process
default appears to have lengthened the time to investigate, introduced more delays for customers, shows bias towards the body complained about and 
defaultdoes not investigate the complaint as stated
default.
default 
default defaultAn external review of PHSO’s new process
default, perhaps involving complainants,
default and determining whether it is actually bringing any benefits to complainants or delivering value for money would be beneficial.
default 
default&#xa0;default19
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultHaving an integrated approach to health and social care complaints. defaultA 
defaultsingle health and social care investigation process which is clearly signposted and consistent across the boundaries
default, mirroring the process at tier 1 would be far more efficient than the current arrangements.
default 
default&#xa0;default20
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultMaking better use of advice and advocacy servicesdefault, and doing more to support vulnerable peopledefault. defaultEngaging more with advice and advocacy services and better signposting to these providers on their website
default would benefit PHSO, the body being investigated and the complainant and give everyone
default – and especially vulnerable people - 
defaultan opportunity to make their voice heard.
default This would also reflect the recognition afforded to advocacy support in the Francis Report, the Government’s response and the Clwyd Hart Review.
default  PHSO might also wish to reflect on the lack of advocacy support for people with Parliamentary complaints.  Many of these complainants are drawn from the most vulnerable and distressed populations in the country and the absence of active lobbying for support for their needs (despite evidence of the effectiveness of advocacy).
default&#xa0;default21
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultHaving a regional presence rather than a national defaultfocusdefault. defaultAs the NHS has changed and there is a greater emphasis on regional or local knowledge, PHSO would benefit from regional 
defaultinvestigators, 
defaultwith greater knowledge and awareness of issues in their area.  This would grow the expertise of the investigators of the bodies within their area and they would be more likely to spot the systemic issues arising on a regional basis than a national one.
